European debt write-downs are inevitable
Berkeley — “That was just the Greek crisis,” or “That was just the Greek and Irish crisis,” people used to think, but not anymore, because it is clearly now a eurozone crisis.
It's both easier and more difficult to deal with than usually thought.
The economics behind this crisis are quite simple.
Greece has fiscal problems.
Ireland's banking sector has issues.
Portugal's private debt market has issues.
Spain has issues in all three areas.
Despite the differences in details, the conclusion is the same: these countries will have to go through a painful process of spending cuts.
To offset the side effects of austerity policies, the usual approach is to combine domestic spending cuts with currency depreciation.
Devaluation would enhance export competitiveness, essentially relying on external demand to make up for domestic demand.
However, these countries are all part of the eurozone and do not have independent currencies to devalue, so they can only rely on internal devaluation instead of external devaluation.
They must reduce wages, pensions, and other costs to boost export competitiveness and expand external demand.
In fact, these crisis-stricken countries have shown considerable determination to tighten their belts.
However, one economic variable has not changed with the adjustments of others: public and private sector debt.
The book value of government accumulated debt has remained unchanged, as have bank debts, except for some owed to ordinary junior creditors.
It is this simple fact that makes the internal devaluation strategy self-contradictory: the more wages and other costs are cut, the heavier the burden of accumulated debt becomes.
The heavier the debt burden becomes, the more public expenditures need to be cut and taxes increased to address the government's and its supporters' (such as banks) debts.
This, in turn, requires further internal devaluation, which raises the debt burden even higher, thus perpetuating the cycle and dragging the economy into recession.
So, for internal devaluation to work, ways must be found to reduce the face value of debt.
Government debt must be restructured.
Bank debt must be converted into equity, and bank debts exceeding assets should be written off.
Mortgage debt must also be writedown.
Policy makers are reluctant to go down this road, and that is understandable.
Contracts are sacred.
Government fears losing credibility with financial markets.
If creditors are mainly from abroad, especially foreign banks, haircuts would drag down other countries.
These concerns are not without merit, but they should not lead to unreasonable conclusions.
The only solutions are internal devaluation or external devaluation.
European leaders must choose between the two options.
They consistently ruled out the option of external devaluation.
But internal devaluation necessarily requires debt restructuring.
Denying this is neither reasonable nor logical.
Debt restructuring is straightforward.
The government can issue a batch of debt with face values discounted by a certain proportion relative to the existing debt.
Bondholders can choose between receiving bonds at par value with a later maturity and lower interest rates, or accepting discounted bonds with earlier maturities and higher interest rates.
This is not cutting-edge technology; it was attempted before.
But it requires three prerequisites to succeed.
First, bondholders must be assured of the safety of the new bonds.
Someone must come forward to guarantee these bonds.
In the 1980s, the U.S. Treasury played the role of guarantor for Latin American debt restructuring under the Brady Plan.
Now, the International Monetary Fund and the German government can take on this responsibility.
Second, countries must act in concert.
Otherwise, one country's restructuring would raise expectations for others, triggering a contagion effect.
Finally, the balance sheets of banks suffering losses from debt restructuring must be strengthened.
These banks need to undergo genuine stress tests rather than the ceremonial ones conducted earlier this year.
If debt restructuring signals capital shortfalls, banks involved must undergo a comprehensive conversion of debt to equity.
If this is not sufficient, the government must inject capital into the affected banks.
This requires countries to act in concert as well.
Once the bank balance sheets are strengthened, it may be possible to restructure mortgage debt, bank debt, and other private sector debts without destabilizing the entire financial system.
Now let's talk about the biggest challenge.
All of this requires firm leadership.
German leaders must acknowledge that their banks are exposed to significant risks in the debt of eurozone peripheral countries, and the situation is urgent.
They must convince the backroom bosses and voters that using public funds to guarantee debt restructuring and bank recapitalization is a necessary condition for internal devaluation; given that Germany urges other EU countries to adopt this strategy, it should shoulder the responsibility of providing guarantees.
In short, European leaders, especially those in Germany, need to make the consequences sound more severe — otherwise, they are in grave danger.
Because that is the reality.
